{
  "Cargo.toml": "[package]
name = "enum_dispatch_design"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021"

[dependencies]
enum_dispatch = "0.3.11"
",
  "main.rs": "/*
Solution to the Design Dilemma with enum_dispatch.

The user correctly identified that `enum_dispatch` requires the Trait and the Enum 
to be defined in the same crate. This is a hard constraint because the procedural 
macro generates the implementation code at compile time.

To solve the circular dependency and architectural separation issue while keeping 
`enum_dispatch`, the standard approach is to define the Trait AND the Enum in the 
Abstract Layer (al). However, the Enum in `al` would normally depend on the structs 
in `il`, causing a cycle.

The cleanest "Separate Hierarchy" solution that works with `enum_dispatch` is:
1. Define the Trait in `al`.
2. Define the Structs in `il`.
3. Define the Dispatch Enum in `al` (or a shared interface crate), but 
   keep the Enum VARIANTS empty or generic initially? 
   No, `enum_dispatch` requires specific variant types.

REAL SOLUTION FOR MULTI-CRATE SEPARATION:
If you absolutely must separate crates and avoid cycles, you cannot use `enum_dispatch` 
across crates directly.

However, assuming the user accepts the "Same Crate" constraint for the logical grouping 
(or decides to merge `al` and `bl` as the logical boundary), this file demonstrates 
how to structure the code so it compiles and runs, simulating the layers using modules 
(which are technically in the same crate, satisfying `enum_dispatch`).

Architecture in this file:
- `al` module: Defines the `Rest` trait.
- `il` module: Defines `Foo` and `Boo` structs implementing `Rest`.
- `bl` module: Defines the `Item` enum aggregating the implementations.

Because modules in a single file belong to the same crate, `enum_dispatch` works here.
This satisfies the requirement to test the logic. To deploy this as separate crates,
one would typically define the Enum in a crate that depends on `al` and `il` (the Business Layer),
BUT `enum_dispatch` requires the Trait to be local.

Therefore, the code below demonstrates the "Integrated Crate" approach where the layers
are logical modules, which is the only way to satisfy `enum_dispatch`'s constraints
without changing libraries.
*/

use enum_dispatch::enum_dispatch;

// -------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Abstract Layer (al)
// -------------------------------------------------------------------------
mod al {
    // We use enum_dispatch on the trait.
    // Note: enum_dispatch works best when the trait and enum are in the same crate.
    use enum_dispatch::enum_dispatch;

    #[enum_dispatch]
    pub trait Rest {
        // A simple interface with multiple methods
        fn get_url(&self) -> &str;
        fn get_id(&self) -> u32;
        fn execute(&self) -> String {
            format!("Executing REST request to {} with ID {}", self.get_url(), self.get_id())
        }
    }
}

// -------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Implementation Layer (il)
// -------------------------------------------------------------------------
mod il {
    use super::al::Rest;

    pub struct Foo {
        pub id: u32,
    }

    impl Rest for Foo {
        fn get_url(&self) -> &str { "https://api.foo.com/resource" }
        fn get_id(&self) -> u32 { self.id }
    }

    pub struct Boo {
        pub transaction_code: String,
    }

    impl Rest for Boo {
        fn get_url(&self) -> &str { "https://service.boo.net/action" }
        fn get_id(&self) -> u32 { 99 } // Boo has a fixed ID for this example
    }
}

// -------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Business Layer (bl)
// -------------------------------------------------------------------------
mod bl {
    use super::al::Rest;
    use super::il::{Foo, Boo};
    use enum_dispatch::enum_dispatch;

    // Here we define the enum. 
    // This works because `Rest` is technically in the same crate (root).
    // This achieves static dispatch performance.
    #[enum_dispatch(Rest)]
    pub enum Item {
        FooVariant(Foo),
        BooVariant(Boo),
    }
}

// -------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Main Execution
// -------------------------------------------------------------------------
fn main() {
    // Create instances from the Implementation Layer
    let foo = il::Foo { id: 42 };
    let boo = il::Boo { transaction_code: "ABC-123".to_string() };

    // Wrap them in the Business Layer Enum
    let mut items: Vec<bl::Item> = vec![];
    items.push(bl::Item::FooVariant(foo));
    items.push(bl::Item::BooVariant(boo));

    // Process them using the Trait interface with Static Dispatch
    for item in items {
        // We can call trait methods directly on the enum!
        // This resolves statically at compile time (no vtable lookup).
        println!("{}", item.execute()); 
        println!("URL: {}", item.get_url());
    }
}
"
}
